Matthew was scheduled to appear in court this Thursday on the abduction charge and reckless driving charges. The cases were postponed until December.

Matthew took the car from his sister and fled Virginia on September 21 after walking into the Charlottesville police station with family members and asking to speak to a detective.

Police were still trying to fill in gaps in the timeline from the night that Jesse Matthew was last seen on surveillance footage with University of Virginia student Hannah Graham at 1.40am in the downtown area.

At a briefing earlier on Monday, investigators asked people who knew Matthew, a former college football lineman and sometime cab driver, to come forward with information so that they can develop a better profile of him. 

This week, dozens of people continued to scour hundreds of square miles in Albemarle County, through woodland and heavy brush, for the missing 18-year-old sophomore.

For the first time ever in Virginia, an aerial drone was being used to search for the missing teen.   

